  "title": "Measuring GitHub Copilot's Impact on Productivity",
  "year": 2024,
  "venue": "Communications of the ACM",
  "study_design_description": "An observational study analyzing 2,631 survey responses from developers using GitHub Copilot, matched to usage telemetry collected from the IDE. Developers were participants in an unpaid technical preview using GitHub Copilot with their everyday programming tasks. Survey responses were collected via email to 17,420 users, with 2,047 responses successfully matched to usage data from a four-week study period (February 10 \u2013 March 6, 2022). The study investigates whether usage measurements of developer interactions with GitHub Copilot can predict perceived productivity as reported by developers.",
  "primary_task_description": "Developers used GitHub Copilot with their everyday programming tasks. When generating whole snippets of code, the system uses a large language model (LLM) to predict what the user might type next (the completion) from the context of what they are working on at the moment (the prompt).",
  "population_description": "2,631 survey responses from developers using GitHub Copilot, matched to usage data. A total of 2,047 responses were successfully matched to usage data from the study period. The respondents included a significant proportion of professional programmers.",
