  "notes": "This is an observational study with no experimental arms or randomized conditions. The study correlates survey responses about perceived productivity with objective usage telemetry from GitHub Copilot. Sample size: 2,631 survey responses analyzed; 2,047 successfully matched to usage data. The paper includes subgroup analyses by experience level and programming language, and temporal analyses of acceptance rate patterns. The correlation between acceptance rate and aggregate productivity (\u03c1 = 0.24) is described as \"high confidence but leaves considerable unexplained variance.\" The study notes several caveats: the validity of acceptance rate as a measure of value is unclear; it is uncertain how long after acceptance one should confirm persistence; and a previous study found no significant correlation between task completion times and survey responses when comparing GitHub Copilot against IntelliCode with 25 participants. All data for time-of-day and weekday analyses were restricted to U.S. users only.",
  "_paper_id": "ziegler"
}